{
  "answer": "In *The Wanderer*, the speaker contemplates the ruins of a once-great hall and utters the bleakest line amid a cascade of losses: \"'Where has the horse gone? Where has the warrior gone? Where the treasure-giver? / Where have the feast-benches gone? Where are the hall-joys? / Alas, the bright cup! Alas, the mailed warrior! / Alas, the prince's pride! How that time has passed, / grown dark under night's helm, as if it never were!'\"[^1]\n\nMirza Ghalib evokes a parallel vertigo of outliving glory in many ghazals, but his bleakest line on domestic ruin—grass overtaking the walls like nature reclaiming a lost world—comes in ghazal 237: \"A wild green sprouts from door and wall, O Ghalib, / I'm in the wilds, and ruin is the spring at home.\"[^2]\n\nThe Wanderer's speaker is closer to despair: his lament surveys a world stripped bare by wyrd (fate), with all earthly bonds loaned and soon empty.[^3] Yet he finds a way to live with it, binding his grief inwardly until wisdom ripens, then seeking eternal stability from the heavenly Father.[^4] Ghalib, by contrast, has made peace with desolation; his couplets transmute personal ruin (an empty house, a wasted heart) into defiant art, where even grief fuels the ghazal's fire.[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Unknown*, *Old English Elegies*, [\"The Wanderer\"](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [\"ug raha hai dar-o-deewaar se sabzah Ghalib\"](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/237-ug-raha-hai-dar-o-deewaar-se-sabzah-ghalib/translation/#p-45d6bf).\n\n[^3]: *Unknown*, *Old English Elegies*, [\"The Wanderer\"](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^4]: *Unknown*, *Old English Elegies*, [\"The Wanderer\"](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).\n\n[^5]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [\"ghar hamara jo na rote bhi to veeran hota\"](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/218-ghar-hamara-jo-na-rote-bhi-to-veeran-hota/translation/#p-52b8ef); [\"Maze jahaan ke apni nazar mein khaak nahin\"](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/134-maze-jahaan-ke-apni-nazar-mein-khaak-nahin/translation/#p-21b277).",
